<p class="lead">
  Markdown is used to format news posts
</p>
<p>
  When you visit a news article, BoarderLine converts the formatting information that was entered when the post was created, and converts it to HTML so a web browser can understand it. For example, <code>**Hello**, I'm writing *Markdown*</code> is converted to <code>&lt;strong&gt;Hello&lt;/strong&gt;, I'm writing &lt;em&gt;Markdown&lt;/em&gt;</code>
</p>

<div class="row">
  <div class="span6">
  <h2>Markdown entered</h2>
    <pre>
      First level header
      =================

      Second level header
      -------------------

      **Bold text**

      *Italic text*

      * Unordered...
      * List

      1. Ordered...
      2. List

      &lt;http://google.com&gt; (link without text)

      [Link with text](http://google.com)

      ```
      #block of code
      ```

      &gt; Quote

      \*Excape characters with backslash\*
    </pre>
  </div>

  <div class="span6">
    <h2>Returned HTML</h2>
    <div class="well">
      <h1>First level header</h1>
